04056nam a22006255i 9780292756489DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211995txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927564897 a10.7560/7555292doi  a(DE-B1597)587061  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a709.01130972811 aStone, Andrea J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImages from the Underworld :bNaj Tunich and the Tradition of Maya Cave Painting /cAndrea J. Stone. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 The Topographic Context of Maya Cave Painting -- t3 A Further Exploration of Topographic Context: The Mesoamerican Landscape and the Cave -- t4 Maya and Mesoamerican Cave Painting: A Survey of Sites and Images -- t5 Naj Tunich: An Introduction to the Site and Its Art -- t6 Images from Naj Tunich -- t7 The Hieroglyphic Inscriptions of Naj Tunich -- t8 A Catalog of Naj Tunich Paintings and Petroglyphs -- t9 Maya Cave Painting: Summary of a Tradition -- tAPPENDIX A The Geologic Context of Maya Cave Paintings -- tAPPENDIX B Standard Cave Map Symbols -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1979, a Kekchi Maya Indian accidentally discovered the entrance to Naj Tunich, a deep cave in the Maya Mountains of El Peten, Guatemala. One of the world's few deep caves that contain rock art, Naj Tunich features figural images and hieroglyphic inscriptions that have helped to revolutionize our understanding of ancient Maya art and ritual. In this book, Andrea Stone takes a comprehensive look at Maya cave painting from Preconquest times to the Colonial period. After surveying Mesoamerican cave and rock painting sites and discussing all twenty-five known painted caves in the Maya area, she focuses extensively on Naj Tunich. Her text analyzes the images and inscriptions, while photographs and line drawings provide a complete visual catalog of the cave art, some of which has been subsequently destroyed by vandals. This important new body of images and texts enlarges our understanding of the Maya view of sacred landscape and the role of caves in ritual. It will be important reading for all students of the Maya, as well as for others interested in cave art and in human relationships with the natural environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aMacLeod, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStone, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVeni, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75552940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292756489423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292756489/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK